{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568029"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19456"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19456"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.37,0.05,0.19,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84760"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12183"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69049"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"889"},{"type":"tags","id":"4267"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of a rapidly growing lump inside his right ear. He works as a retired farmer and has extensive sun damage to his skin. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm firm, pink, dome-shaped nodule on the conchal bowl of his right ear with surrounding solar keratoses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Malignant melanoma","Keratoacanthoma","Fibroxanthoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents the classic triad for atypical \u003Cstrong\u003Efibroxanthoma\u003C/strong\u003E: rapid growth over weeks, sun-damaged skin, and older age. These tumours typically present as dome-shaped nodules on sun-exposed areas, particularly the head and neck including the ear, of elderly patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a pearly nodule with telangiectasia and grows slowly over months to years. While it commonly occurs on sun-exposed areas including the ear, the rapid growth pattern in this case makes it less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents as a scaling, indurated plaque or nodule that develops gradually over months. While it is associated with sun damage and frequently occurs on the ear, the rapid growth pattern is atypical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a pigmented lesion with irregular borders and colour variation. While it can occur on sun-exposed areas, the presentation as a rapidly growing pink nodule would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratoacanthoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a rapidly growing dome-shaped nodule, but characteristically has a central keratin plug and tends to be more symmetrical than fibroxanthoma. It also typically undergoes spontaneous regression over 4-6 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis is recognising the combination of rapid growth (weeks rather than months), location on sun-damaged skin, and elderly patient age. While biopsy is required for definitive diagnosis, the clinical presentation strongly suggests atypical fibroxanthoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atypical fibroxanthoma is a rapidly growing tumour occurring on sun-damaged skin in older patients.","The key diagnostic features are rapid growth over weeks, location on sun-exposed areas like the ear, and older age.","Unlike other skin cancers which grow slowly over months, atypical fibroxanthoma presents as a rapidly enlarging nodule."],"references":["Agaimy A. The many faces of Atypical fibroxanthoma. Semin Diagn Pathol. 2023;40(4):306-312. doi:10.1053/j.semdp.2023.06.001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69049"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19456"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21534"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21534"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BBRpJO26IgoHvqTBjpIyR3FB1zUp0Y.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BBRpJO26IgoHvqTBjpIyR3FB1zUp0Y.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69049"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T16:06:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T16:08:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12183"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings",